With the disappearance of the formulary system this complicated procedure necessarily passed away3 its very complication depended on the formula. justinian tells us himself (§ 8 inf.) that in his day interdicta (stricto sensu) were no longer issued: in the opening paragraph os the Title he speaks of interdicts ⁶ seu actionibus quae pro his exercentur‚’ with which may be compared the Title of Dig. 43. 1 ‘de interdictis sive extraordinariis actionibus quae pro his competunt! An interdiu, in his time, may fairly be described as the trial by ordinary action, commenced in the ordinary way, of questions which in the formulary period would have been tried in the complicated mode described by Gaius and more particularly os questions relating to possession—‘ inter- dicta autem licet in extraordinariis iudiciis proprie locum non habent, tamen ad exemplum eorum res agitur’ Cod. 8. 1. 3. The only features of difference between them and an ordinary action are t‘o be explained by supposing that the questions on which they lay were thought to deserve a somewhat more summary trial than others: hence the directions in the Code (eg. 8. 1. 43 8. 2. 3; 8. 4. 8; 11. 47. 14), to judges to try interdicts with all possible despatch‚ and the rule that the operation of a decision on the interdict unde vi (which may be taken as a type of the rest) shall not be suspended by appeal ; Cod. 7. 69. ’
